    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-07-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-07-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="647"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d647">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.00/80</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Secretary to the President</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sanders</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lynn, Mass.</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-07-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 10, 1925.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 14.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Grew</hi>: This will acknowledge your favor of
                    the 7th addressed to the President,<note n="82" xml:id="d647fn82">Not
                        printed.</note> in which you enclosed a copy of a note received by the
                    Department from the British Chargé d’Affaires<note n="83" xml:id="d647fn83">Note
                        No. 677 of July 3, <ref target="#pg_770">p. 770</ref>.</note> setting forth
                    the comments of the British Government on the issues <pb facs="0904" n="778"
                        xml:id="pg_778"/> raised by the Chinese Government’s identic notes to the
                    Legations in Peking of June 24th, and also your letter of July 8th<note n="84"
                        xml:id="d647fn84">Not printed.</note> in which you enclosed two additional
                    notes received from the British Chargé d’Affaires on the same subject, dated,
                    respectively, July 6th and 7th.<note n="85" xml:id="d647fn85">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_775">pp. 775</ref> and <ref
                            target="#pg_776">776</ref>.</note> The President has directed me to
                    advise you that he thinks in the circumstances the Secretary of State should use
                    his judgment but cooperate as far as possible with the other interested powers,
                    using great care not to have China think there is a division of counsel.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Everett Sanders</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
